sort.markdown:
### [sort](https://docs.dolphindb.com/en/Functions/s/sort.html)



#### Syntax

sort(X, \[ascending=true])

Please refer to [sort!](https://docs.dolphindb.com/en/Functions/s/sort!.html). The only difference between sort and sort! is that the latter assigns the result to X and thus changing the value of X after the execution.

#### Arguments

**X** is a vector.

**ascending** (optional) is a Boolean scalar indicating whether to sort *X* in ascending order or descending order. The default value is true (ascending order).

#### Details

Return a sorted vector in ascending/descending order.

#### Examples

```
x=9 1 5;
x;
// output
[9,1,5]

y=sort(x);
y;
// output
[1,5,9]

sort(x, false);
// output
[9,5,1]

x=1 4 2 5 6 3$2:3;
x;
```

| #0 | #1 | #2 |
| -- | -- | -- |
| 1  | 2  | 6  |
| 4  | 5  | 3  |

```
sort x;
```

| #0 | #1 | #2 |
| -- | -- | -- |
| 1  | 3  | 5  |
| 2  | 4  | 6  |

The `sort!` function change the value of input after sorting.

```
x=9 1 5;
